AcceptRA] Section Options<a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this=
 headline" href=3D"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd=
.network.html#%5BIPv6AcceptRA%5D%20Section%20Options">=C2=B6</a></h2><p>The=
 "<code class=3D"literal">[IPv6AcceptRA]</code>" section configures the IPv=
6 Router Advertisement
      (RA) client, if it is enabled with the <code class=3D"varname">IPv6Ac=
ceptRA=3D</code> setting described
      above:</p><div class=3D"variablelist"><dl class=3D"variablelist"><dt =
id=3D"UseDNS=3D1"><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">UseDNS=3D</c=
ode></span><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this term" href=3D=
"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#UseD=
NS=3D1">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>When true (the default), the DNS servers rece=
ived in the Router Advertisement will be used and take
            precedence over any statically configured ones.</p><p>This corr=
esponds to the <code class=3D"option">nameserver</code> option in <a href=
=3D"http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/resolv.conf.5.html"><span class=3D=
"citerefentry"><span class=3D"refentrytitle">resolv.conf</span>(5)</span></=
a>.</p></dd><dt id=3D"UseDomains=3D1"><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"v=
arname">UseDomains=3D</code></span><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permali=
nk to this term" href=3D"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/s=
ystemd.network.html#UseDomains=3D1">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Takes a boolean a=
rgument, or the special value "<code class=3D"literal">route</code>". When =
true, the domain name
            received via IPv6 Router Advertisement (RA) will be used as DNS=
 search domain over this link, similar to
            the effect of the <code class=3D"option">Domains=3D</code> sett=
ing. If set to "<code class=3D"literal">route</code>", the domain name
            received via IPv6 RA will be used for routing DNS queries only,=
 but not for searching, similar to the
            effect of the <code class=3D"option">Domains=3D</code> setting =
when the argument is prefixed with
            "<code class=3D"literal">~</code>". Defaults to false.</p><p>It=
 is recommended to enable this option only on trusted networks, as setting =
this affects resolution
            of all host names, in particular of single-label names. It is g=
enerally safer to use the supplied domain
            only as routing domain, rather than as search domain, in order =
to not have it affect local resolution of
            single-label names.</p><p>When set to true, this setting corres=
ponds to the <code class=3D"option">domain</code> option in <a href=3D"http=
://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/resolv.conf.5.html"><span class=3D"citeref=
entry"><span class=3D"refentrytitle">resolv.conf</span>(5)</span></a>.</p><=
/dd><dt id=3D"RouteTable=3Dnum1"><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varnam=
e">RouteTable=3D<em class=3D"replaceable"><code>num</code></em></code></spa=
n><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this term" href=3D"https://=
www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#RouteTable=3D=
num1">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>The table identifier for the routes received in=
 the Router Advertisement
            (a number between 1 and 4294967295, or 0 to unset).
            The table can be retrieved using <span class=3D"command"><stron=
g>ip route show table <em class=3D"replaceable"><code>num</code></em></stro=
ng></span>.
            </p></dd></dl></div></div><div class=3D"refsect1"><a name=3D"id=
-1.15"></a><h2 id=3D"[DHCPServer] Section Options">[DHCPServer] Section Opt=
ions<a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this headline" href=3D"ht=
tps://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#%5BDHCP=
Server%5D%20Section%20Options">=C2=B6</a></h2><p>The "<code class=3D"litera=
l">[DHCPServer]</code>" section contains
    settings for the DHCP server, if enabled via the
    <code class=3D"varname">DHCPServer=3D</code> option described above:</p=
><div class=3D"variablelist"><dl class=3D"variablelist"><dt id=3D"PoolOffse=
t=3D"><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">PoolOffset=3D</code>, </=
span><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">PoolSize=3D</code></span>=
<a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this term" href=3D"https://ww=
w.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#PoolOffset=3D">=
=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Configures the pool of addresses to hand out. The poo=
l
        is a contiguous sequence of IP addresses in the subnet configured f=
or
        the server address, which does not include the subnet nor the broad=
cast
        address. <code class=3D"varname">PoolOffset=3D</code> takes the off=
set of the pool
        from the start of subnet, or zero to use the default value.
        <code class=3D"varname">PoolSize=3D</code> takes the number of IP a=
ddresses in the
        pool or zero to use the default value. By default, the pool starts =
at
        the first address after the subnet address and takes up the rest of
        the subnet, excluding the broadcast address. If the pool includes
        the server address (the default), this is reserved and not handed
        out to clients.</p></dd><dt id=3D"DefaultLeaseTimeSec=3D"><span cla=
ss=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">DefaultLeaseTimeSec=3D</code>, </span><=
span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">MaxLeaseTimeSec=3D</code></span=
><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this term" href=3D"https://w=
ww.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#DefaultLeaseTi=
meSec=3D">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Control the default and maximum DHCP lease
        time to pass to clients. These settings take time values in seconds=
 or
        another common time unit, depending on the suffix. The default
        lease time is used for clients that did not ask for a specific
        lease time. If a client asks for a lease time longer than the
        maximum lease time, it is automatically shortened to the
        specified time. The default lease time defaults to 1h, the
        maximum lease time to 12h. Shorter lease times are beneficial
        if the configuration data in DHCP leases changes frequently
        and clients shall learn the new settings with shorter
        latencies. Longer lease times reduce the generated DHCP
        network traffic.</p></dd><dt id=3D"EmitDNS=3D"><span class=3D"term"=
><code class=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</code>, </span><span class=3D"term"><co=
de class=3D"varname">DNS=3D</code></span><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"P=
ermalink to this term" href=3D"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd=
/man/systemd.network.html#EmitDNS=3D">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Configures whet=
her the DHCP leases handed out
        to clients shall contain DNS server information. The
        <code class=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</code> setting takes a boolean a=
rgument
        and defaults to "<code class=3D"literal">yes</code>". The DNS serve=
rs to
        pass to clients may be configured with the
        <code class=3D"varname">DNS=3D</code> option, which takes a list of=
 IPv4
        addresses. If the <code class=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</code> option =
is
        enabled but no servers configured, the servers are
        automatically propagated from an "uplink" interface that has
        appropriate servers set. The "uplink" interface is determined
        by the default route of the system with the highest
        priority. Note that this information is acquired at the time
        the lease is handed out, and does not take uplink interfaces
        into account that acquire DNS or NTP server information at a
        later point. DNS server propagation does not take
        <code class=3D"filename">/etc/resolv.conf</code> into account. Also=
, note
        that the leases are not refreshed if the uplink network
        configuration changes. To ensure clients regularly acquire the
        most current uplink DNS server information, it is thus
        advisable to shorten the DHCP lease time via
        <code class=3D"varname">MaxLeaseTimeSec=3D</code> described
        above.</p></dd><dt id=3D"EmitNTP=3D"><span class=3D"term"><code cla=
ss=3D"varname">EmitNTP=3D</code>, </span><span class=3D"term"><code class=
=3D"varname">NTP=3D</code></span><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink=
 to this term" href=3D"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/sys=
temd.network.html#EmitNTP=3D">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Similar to the <code cl=
ass=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</code> and
        <code class=3D"varname">DNS=3D</code> settings described above, the=
se
        settings configure whether and what NTP server information
        shall be emitted as part of the DHCP lease. The same syntax,
        propagation semantics and defaults apply as for
        <code class=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</code> and
        <code class=3D"varname">DNS=3D</code>.</p></dd><dt id=3D"EmitRouter=
=3D"><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">EmitRouter=3D</code></spa=
n><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this term" href=3D"https://=
www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#EmitRouter=3D=
">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Similar to the <code class=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</=
code>
        setting described above, this setting configures whether the
        DHCP lease should contain the router option. The same syntax,
        propagation semantics and defaults apply as for
        <code class=3D"varname">EmitDNS=3D</code>.</p></dd><dt id=3D"EmitTi=
mezone=3D"><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">EmitTimezone=3D</co=
de>, </span><span class=3D"term"><code class=3D"varname">Timezone=3D</code>=
</span><a class=3D"headerlink" title=3D"Permalink to this term" href=3D"htt=
ps://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.network.html#EmitTime=
zone=3D">=C2=B6</a></dt><dd><p>Configures whether the DHCP leases handed ou=
t
        to clients shall contain timezone information. The
        <code class=3D"varname">EmitTimezone=3D</code> setting takes a bool=
ean
        argument and defaults to "<code class=3D"literal">yes</code>". The
        <code class=3D"varname">Timezone=3D</code> setting takes a timezone=
 string
        (such as "<code class=3D"literal">Europe/Berlin</code>" or
        "<code class=3D"literal">UTC</code>") to pass to clients. If no exp=
licit
        timezone is set, the system timezone of the local host is
        propagated, as determined by the
        <code class=3D"filename">/etc/localtime</code> symlink.</p></dd></d=
l></div></div><div class=3D"refsect1"><a name=3D"id-1.16"></a><h2 id=3D"[IP=
v6PrefixDelegation] Section Options">[IPv6PrefixDelegation] Section Options=
